div.p:
The hierarchical levels of dictionary entries are declared as shown in the following
DTD fragment. As may be seen, the content model forentry specifies that
entries do not nest, that homographs nest within entries, and that senses nest
within entries, homographs, or senses, and may be nested to any depth to reflect the
embedding of sub-senses. Any of the top-level constituents
(def,usg, form, etc.) can appear at any level (i.e.,
within entries, homographs, or senses). 
&superEntry;

&entry;
&entryFree;
&hom;
&sense;
&dictScrap;

The formal declarations for the elements of the form group are
    these: 
&form;
&orth;
&pron;
&hyph;
&syll;
&stress;
&gram;
&gen;
&number;
&case;
&per;
&tns;
&mood;
&iType;

The classes of morphological elements, and of elements allowed within the
form group, are declared thus: 
&model.morphLike;
&model.formPart;

The following gives the formal declarations for elements in the
grammatical-information group.
&gramGrp;
&pos;
&subc;
&colloc;

The class of elements allowed within the gramGrp element is declared thus.
The class morphInfo is defined above in section . 
&model.gramPart;

The formal definition of these elements is as follows: 
&tr;
&trans;

The following gives the formal definition of usg
andlbl: 
&usg;
&lbl;

The class of headword references is defined thus: 
&model.ptrLike.form;
&att.ptrLike.form;

The formal declaration for headword reference elements is: 
&oRef;
&oVar;
&pRef;
&pVar;

The attributes provided for all dictionary-specific elements and documented in this
section are defined thus:
&att.lexicographic;
